<blockquote>
<p>to be the people in the foundation who can't afford to be too hardened, because they're the people whose specific job it is, at the end of the day, to care.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>That's a very interesting interpretation. However the above line and other stuff like</p>
<blockquote>
<p>I will admit, my first reaction to that was; ‘Ah, yes, the other-other white meat.’</p>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
<p>Dictatorships don’t usually get ethics committees, no.</p>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
<p>Welcome to SCP ethics. Where it’s necessary to be politically correct about baby-culling.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>don't really read as humanizing, or even how somebody would talk, in that situation. I mean, maybe this is the first time they're doing this (even as I'd expect this is meant to be taken as one in a very long line of roundtables?) but even then these are p.h.d.'s and a black-ops assassin. I wouldn't expect total starkness - in fact I'm pretty sure that'd work to its detriment, as you say - but the way the characters are written <em>right now</em>, I don't really buy 'em. Of course that's relative, and general reception appears to be very positive, so it's probably just a matter of taste.</p>

							</div>

								
					
